Q74: I received a link to this study in an email stating that it was a follow-up. The questions appeared to be the same as those that I answered previously. Maybe that is the point.

I found that sometimes the question was tricky because it was based around "childhood diseases".  There are many types of diseases but I focused on MMR. Children need illness in order for their immune system to be strong. So some childhood diseases are not dangerous and actually a necessary evil.
I really think some of the answers I picked would have benefited from the (optional!) opportunity to explain why I picked what I did.
I have a daughter with chronic medical needs. I have to vaccinate to give her the best chance possible of fighting off illness. I am pretty biased towards vaccines because of her needs.

Discussing vaccines is a delicate art almost like religion or politics. When offended, people quickly 'double-down'. I really appreciated my Doctor handing me objective pamphlets in a nonjudgemental way and asking me to consider the literature, it removed the embarrassment and confrontation.
comments: I just wrote them on the previous page.

Q74: Thank you for allowing me to participate!
Very interesting study!! Thank you for your work in this area.

The only thing that didn't affect me as probably intended was the 106 fever passage. I am typically pro- Western medicine, but I do not have the fear of fever that a lot of Americans have. I understand that higher fevers are sometimes correlated with more serious illnesses, but that is not always the case. And it's not unheard of for a baby or toddler to have high fevers. I believe you pay attention to symptoms, overall demeanor, hydration, etc., not the number on the thermometer.
